☢️ User Manual: Pixoo Designer OS
Welcome to the Pixoo Designer creation terminal. This tool allows you to design static or animated screens for your Divoom Pixoo 64 via Home Assistant, bypassing the limits of the native integration.

1. Page Management and Render Modes
By clicking the [+] button in the top bar, you create a new page. The system will prompt you to choose a type:

Components: The free-form creation page. You start with a blank 64x64 canvas. Ideal for static dashboards or widget-based interfaces.

MultiGif: The advanced mode. Allows you to set an animated GIF background and overlay real-time HA sensors on top of it. Requires server-side "baking".

Clock / Weather / Fuel: Shortcuts to native Divoom app screens (Official Clocks, Weather, Fuel Prices).

Image / GIF: Simply displays a static image or full-screen animation (via a local URL or web).

2. The "Components" Mode (WYSIWYG Editor)
This is the core of the system. Select a tool from the left sidebar to add it to the Canvas.

Available Tools:

Data: Static Text, Home Assistant Sensor, Current Time (Datetime), Native Weather Icon.

Media: LaMetric animated icons, Image/SVG (Local upload or Drag & Drop), Material Design Icons (MDI).

Shapes: Rectangles, Rounded Rectangles, Circles. Since HA's native integration does not support circles or rounded corners natively, read the "Freeze" section below carefully.

Progress: Progress bars linked to an HA sensor, with conditional color management (e.g., red if < 20%).

3. ⚠️ The Crucial Concept: "Freeze" (Figer) into a Layer
Why Freeze?
The native divoom_pixoo integration in Home Assistant is picky. It only understands simple text, basic rectangles, and static images. It does not understand MDI icons, circles, complex gradients, or color filters applied in the browser.

How does it work?
To bypass this limit, Pixoo Designer uses rasterization. When you finish designing a complex shape, an MDI icon, or applying filters to an image:

Select the element.

In the right panel, click the pink 📸 Figer PNG (Freeze Layer) button.

Magic happens: The script takes an invisible "photo" of the element, sends it to the HA server (which stores it in /config/www/pixoo_media/), and replaces your editable element with a pixel-perfect frozen Image.

"Freeze All" Tip: If you've composed a whole screen with lots of shapes and icons, go to the system menu (SYS) at the top right and click "FIGER TOUT (PNG)" (Freeze All). The system will automatically convert all unsupported elements into Home Assistant-ready images.

4. Image Processing (Ultra Custom Mode)
When you import an image, the right panel displays image processing (Dithering) options to adapt it to the Pixoo LED screen. Select the rendering mode from the dropdown list:

Clean: Cleans near-white pixels to avoid artifacts.

Premium: Applies the Floyd-Steinberg algorithm with 3-3-2 quantization (reduces the image to the exact hardware palette of the Pixoo for optimal rendering).

Portrait: Softens the image before the Premium algorithm (ideal for faces or album covers).

Ultra Custom: Unlocks 8 live sliders (Exposure, Edges, Saturation, Smart Blur, Pan, Zoom). Tune the image perfectly, then click 📸 Figer PNG to confirm and save it.

5. LaMetric Integration and MDI Icons
LaMetric: Add a LaMetric component, enter the desired icon ID (findable in the built-in library via the "Biblio" button) and click "Charger" (Load). The icon (static or GIF) will snap to the grid.

MDI: Search for any Material Design Icon, adjust its color and size. Reminder: Don't forget to "Freeze" it before exporting.

6. Export and Publish to Pixoo
The top right bar contains your deployment tools:

ENVOYER (Live Test): Instantly pushes the current page to the Pixoo for a visual test. The rendering is calculated in real-time by the script and sent via a direct API call.

PUBLIER (Final Save): * If you are on a "Components" page, this updates the YAML code in the right side panel.

If you are on a "MultiGif" page, this launches the "Baking" (Cuisson). The Python server will generate the final GIF with all overlays, save it in /pixoo_media_gif/, and provide you with the final YAML code featuring the local URL to integrate into your Home Assistant configuration.

SYS (System): The burger menu allows you to save the complete project, clean the media folders on the server, or open the Debug terminal.
